    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the lesson. I also want to make sure they understand why this specific doctrine is considered so essential in our legal system compared to just \"procedural\" due process. Could you expand on that part? Like, why is substantive due process specifically the better or more effective way to secure these liberties?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process only ensures fair *methods* for the government to act, like holding a public hearing, while substantive due process protects the actual *content* of rights themselves from being ignored. This distinction is crucial because procedural rules alone cannot stop a government from unjustly depriving citizens of fundamental liberties, such as the right to privacy or bodily autonomy. Substantive due process is the stronger tool because it allows the judiciary to actively define and defend these core human rights against legislative or executive overreach, ensuring that the Constitution's values are realized even when laws are silent or oppressive.",
      "source": "target",
